	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_01.jpg"/></p>
			<p>Resident of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_kirshenblum_refoel">Refoel Kirshenblum</persName> tells:</p>

			<p>I was born in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765876/lublin.html">Lublin</placeName> in <date when="1905">1905</date> to
				religious <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">parents</term>. I am trained as a builder,
				but during the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">occupation</term> I had different
				jobs: loaded timber on the railway, took out rubbish and mixed concrete. I married in <date when="1928">1928</date>, my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">wife</term> and three <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">perished</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName> on the <date when="1942-11-10"
					>10th of November 1942</date>. Besides that, I lost my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822"
					type="subject">father</term>, my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">mother</term>
				and my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">brother</term> with his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">wife</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term>.</p>
			<p>Since <date when="1928">1928</date>, I live in the town of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html"
					>Siemiatycze</placeName>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7531460/bielsk.html">Bielsk</placeName> district, voivodeship of
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/776069/bialystok.html">Bialystok</placeName>. Around 5000 Jews lived in the town, that is,
				66 percent of the total population. Most Jews worked in the industry of ceramics, in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject">factory</term> of accessories for shoemakers and in
				shoemakers’ and tailors’ workshops. There were also lots of artisans who worked at home and small shopkeepers.</p>
			<p>On the day of the encirclement, that is, on the <date when="1942-11-02">2nd of November 1942</date>, around 300 Jews from surrounding
				towns and villages were driven to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName>. Because
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName> was a border town, right near the
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/697134/pivdennyy-buh.html">Bug river</placeName>, the was no possibility to escape to
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8354411/union-of-soviet-socialist-republics.html">Russia</placeName>, the town had been
				taken by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Germans</term> already at dawn of the
					<date when="1941-06-23">23rd of June 1941</date>.</p>
			<p>In the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> that had been created every day
				about ten Jews would <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">die</term>, and there were no
				births. There were a few cases of mental <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject"
					>illness</term>. During the first days of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject"
					>German occupation</term> the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> forced the
				whole Jewish population (including <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>,
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> and the elderly) to remove grass
				from stones by their bare hands and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term>
				three Jews, because it appeared to the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-477" type="subject">overseers</term></p>
			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_02.jpg"/></p>
			<p>that they were not going to work with enough enthusiasm. We were soon obliged to wear <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-338" type="subject">yellow patches</term>. The local residents together
				with a few <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> from <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-433">Organisation Todt</orgName>, that had just arrived, decided to bury
				the beautiful <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-001129">Lenin</persName> monument that stood in the
				marketplace of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName>. The whole Jewish population
				was dragged out to participate in this shameful activity and people were beaten extremely cruelly. One Jew was thrown into the river
				while still alive, and he <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">perished</term>. [Another
				one] was dressed in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-756" type="subject">Torah</term> crown and a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-756" type="subject">tallit</term> and forced to hold a eulogy to <persName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-001129">Lenin</persName> from a tribune and then to rejoice: <q>Down
					with the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/8354411/union-of-soviet-socialist-republics.html">Soviet Union</placeName>!</q>
				Jews were forced to cut off the head from the <persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-001129"
					>Lenin</persName> monument but they refused to do it. The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> and the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Polish</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1119" type="subject">police</term> started to beat them. The bandits
				themselves smashed the monument and ordered to carry the pieces to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-750" type="subject">Jewish cemetery</term>. Only those who were found in
				possession of some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">meat</term> where <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598" type="subject">arrested</term>, because Jews were forbidden to eat
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">meat</term> except the tiny amount of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bones</term> provided to the Jews by the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>.</p>
			<p>In <date when="1941-08">August 1941</date> Jews had to pay a contribution of 140 thousand roubles and they were also subject to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">forced labour</term>, such as to clean rubble from
				buildings destroyed by the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> artillery, to transport construction materials.
				The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> lacked horses acutely, so they forced the Jews to construct a railway
				first and then to transport the materials with bare hands (without locomotives).</p>
			<p>All real estate that belonged to Jews was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-585" type="subject"
					>confiscated</term> and they were forced to give away all kinds of possessions, such as furniture,</p>
			<p><pb n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_03.jpg"/></p>
			<p>bed linen, dishes, gold etc. <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> would also pillage Jewish homes under all kinds
				of pretexts.</p>
			<p>Jews were allowed to show themselves in the street only for 3 hours a day, from 3 to 5 PM. Except during these three hours, we were
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-339" type="subject">forbidden</term> to leave the apartments, even
				in order to relieve ourselves. We were also forbidden to open a window and to look into the street.</p>
			<p>In <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto">Siemiatycze</placeName> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> was created on the <date
					when="1942-08-02">2nd of August 1942</date>. During the moving to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> checked all the packages and took away valuables. Every <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> resident had 1,1 square metre of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">living space</term>, the height of the ceiling was not
				more than 2,5 meters.</p>
			<p><term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> threated the newly created <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-579" type="subject">Judenrat</term> and the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-480" type="subject">Jewish police</term> very badly. Once the 11 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-554" type="subject">Jewish councilors</term> (except the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-554" type="subject">chairman</term>) were ordered to clean the toilets of
				the town and then transport the waste outside the town. There were no cases when the Jewish administration would give away Jews into
					<term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> hands. Jews had to go to work outside the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> every day. <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> ordered that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> quota for the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> was 120 grams of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term> for a working person daily and 60 grams
				for someone that did not work. Once in a fortnight – 100 grams of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
					type="subject">bones</term>, only for the workers. Those who went to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> would secretly bring back <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> in their pockets. There were no
				workshops or <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929" type="subject">factories</term> inside the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>. We paid a special tax to the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-579"
					type="subject">Judenrat</term> was taking money from the Jews all the time in order to bribe their way out of smaller troubles.
				There was a canteen in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> that</p>
			<p><pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_04.jpg"/></p>
			<p>prepared up to 1500 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">lunches</term> a day.</p>
			<p>There were some cases of previously freethinking persons who fell into a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-724" type="subject">religious</term> mood in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>.</p>
			<p>Our <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto">Siemiatycze ghetto</placeName> existed for
				three months overall. The despair was immense, because we knew that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject">ghetto liquidation</term> had started in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1106" type="ghetto">Warsaw</placeName>. As <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName> was annexed to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Third Reich</term>, we believed that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject">liquidation</term> of the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto">Siemiatycze ghetto</placeName> would not come so
				soon, and the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> would repeatedly reassure us about it.</p>
			<p>On Monday, the <date when="1942-11-02">2nd of November 1942</date>, at 4.30 AM, when we noticed that the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> was surrounded by the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> and the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-429">SS</orgName>, people started to cut through the barbed wires and run
				in a chaotic fashion. The <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> opened fire and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term> a few hundred Jews. A small number
				managed to run away into the woods. There they founded a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-248"
					type="subject">Jewish partisan</term> unit comprising a hundred men. In autumn <date when="1943">1943</date> this unit was largely
				destroyed by the <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term> of Jews from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName> was carried out by the <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> only. Although after the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term> of the Jews signs menacing to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shoot</term> anyone that comes near were hung out in
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>, no one actually guarded it, so
				the local residents would enter into Jewish homes, owners of which were in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName>, at night and pillage Jewish
				possessions. They even rejoiced because of the Jewish misfortunes, but on the other hand, they were also afraid, feeling that the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-529" type="subject">extermination</term> of the</p>
			<p><pb n="5" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_05.jpg"/></p>
			<p>Jews is the beginning of their own <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-529" type="subject"
					>extermination</term>.</p>
			<p>Based on the testimony of <persName ref="#ehri_et_rak_binyomin">Binyomin Rak</persName>, a resident of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/759320/siemiatycze.html">Siemiatycze</placeName>, I know that the final <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-551" type="subject">liquidation</term> of the <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto">Siemiatycze ghetto</placeName> happened in the
				following way.</p>

			<p><q>The Jews that had stayed in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> were
					packed into freight cars and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transported</term>
					through <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/773802/czeremcha.html">Czeremcha</placeName>-<placeName
						ref="http://www.geonames.org/776069/bialystok.html">Białystok</placeName>-<placeName
						ref="http://www.geonames.org/765328/malkinia-gorna.html">Małkinia</placeName>-<placeName
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName>. Although there is a much
					shorter way from <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto">Siemiatycze</placeName>
					to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName> through <placeName
						ref="http://www.geonames.org/758626/sokolow-podlaski.html">Sokołów Podlaski</placeName> (2 hours), the victims were <term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">transported</term> by such a long route on purpose
					in order for them to lose orientation. In the evening we arrived to <placeName
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName>, but we were kept in the cars
					during the whole night. Only in the morning everyone was forced into a <term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-499" type="subject">gas chamber</term> and <term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term>. I, as a qualified carpenter, was
					given a job in the workshops of <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp"
						>Treblinka</placeName> and managed to survive.</q></p>
			<p>About half a kilometer before <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/765328/malkinia-gorna.html">Małkinia</placeName> I jumped from
				the moving train through the little upper window. The window was very narrow and I had to take off my outerwear and jump into a - 12
				degree frost wearing only a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shirt</term>. A few
				dozen persons from other cars also took this desperate step, but the guards <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> them all because they were a good target
				for <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> bullets in a white field covered with snow. I alone survived because I
				did not start running away through the fields, but stood next to a car and pulled a <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>German</term> guard by his coat. He turned around and dropped his automatic gun. I quickly picked up the</p>
			<p><pb n="6" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010107_06.jpg"/></p>
			<p>gun, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> the guard and took his revolver. I
				managed to do it all, because I was in one of the last cars and when I jumped, I landed towards the very end of a long train, where
				there was only a solitary <term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> soldier. During the first month after running away
				I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hid</term> by a few <term
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> in different villages. On the <date when="1942-12-04">4th of December 1942</date>
				I met five more Jews from <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-1068" type="ghetto"
					>Siemiatycze</placeName> in the area around town and we dug a bunker for ourselves under a stable with the help of its owner, a
					<term ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Pole</term>. There I stayed until the coming of the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName>.</p>
			<p>Written down by: <persName ref="#ehri_et_shtokfish_dovid">Shtokfish Dovid</persName></p>
			<p><date when="1945-04">April 1945</date></p>
